---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Portal: Particle Acceleration in Jets - ArXiv Atlas";

import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Portal: Particle Acceleration in Jets</h1>

    <div class="infobox">
      <h3 class="infobox-title">Portal</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>Type:</th><td>Thematic portal</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Papers:</th><td>1</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Concept pages:</th><td>10</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>This portal collects knowledge about <strong>particle acceleration mechanisms in astrophysical jets</strong> — from the basic physics of shock waves and diffusive acceleration to the specialized conditions at recollimation shocks in sub-relativistic outflows. The topic spans undergraduate-level fluid dynamics to cutting-edge research on PeVatron candidates among microquasars and Seyfert galaxies.</p>

    <h2 id="key-questions">Key questions</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Can recollimation shocks in sub-relativistic jets accelerate particles to PeV energies?</li>
      <li>How does the turbulence spectrum (Bohm vs Kraichnan vs Kolmogorov) affect maximum particle energy?</li>
      <li>What role do jet cocoons play in shaping hadronic emission from escaped cosmic rays?</li>
      <li>How do oblique-shock geometries modify the standard DSA picture?</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="foundations">Foundational concepts</h2>
    <p>Start here for background:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/shock-waves" text="Shock waves" /> — Rankine–Hugoniot conditions, compression ratios, and heating</li>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/astrophysical-jets" text="Astrophysical jets" /> — overview of jet launching, collimation, and morphology</li>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/particle-acceleration-basics" text="Particle acceleration basics" /> — how particles gain energy in astrophysical environments</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="core-mechanisms">Core mechanisms</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/diffusive-shock-acceleration" text="Diffusive shock acceleration (DSA)" /> — the leading acceleration process at shocks</li>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/particle-acceleration-oblique-shocks" text="Particle acceleration at oblique shocks" /> — how shock geometry affects efficiency</li>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/recollimation-shocks" text="Recollimation shocks" /> — standing shocks formed by cocoon pressure in jets</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="jet-dynamics">Jet dynamics &amp; structure</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/relativistic-jets" text="Relativistic jets" /> — fast outflows from AGN and compact objects</li>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/jet-cocoon-systems" text="Jet-cocoon systems" /> — the dynamical interplay between jets and their envelopes</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="key-papers">Featured papers</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/2603.16647" text="Peretti et al. (2026)" /> — Particle acceleration at recollimation shocks in sub-relativistic jets</li>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Bromberg_2011" text="Bromberg et al. (2011)" /> — Foundational analytic jet-cocoon framework</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="open-problems">Open problems</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Multi-dimensional transport:</strong> Current models are 1D; lateral escape and 3D shock geometry remain to be incorporated.</li>
      <li><strong>Guide-field effects:</strong> Ordered magnetic fields at oblique shocks may suppress or enhance acceleration (<a href="https://doi.org/10.1086/166490">Kirk 1989</a>; Bell 2011).</li>
      <li><strong>Relativistic extension:</strong> The sub-relativistic framework needs generalization for fast AGN jets and blazars.</li>
      <li><strong>Hadronic signatures:</strong> Escaped protons illuminating cocoons could produce detectable gamma-ray and neutrino emission — predictions await detailed modeling.</li>
    </ul>
  </main>
</Base>
